The TLDR on Context Engineering
I write extensively about prompts because they're genuinely powerful=E2=80=
=94I've seen how the right prompt engineering can transform AI interactions=
=2E But I've realized it's time to open=
 the aperture and talk about something=
 bigger.
While I've been optimizing individual prompts, something more fundamental h=
as been emerging: context engineering=E2=80=94the systematic design of envi=
ronments where AI systems discover and synthesize knowledge, not just respo=
nd to our carefully crafted messages.
Prompts remain crucial, but they're one instrument in an orchestra of conte=
xt systems. The real opportunity isn't just better prompts; it's architecti=
ng the entire space where machine intelligence operates.
The breakthrough lies in understanding two distinct layers that must work i=
n harmony:
Deterministic Context (Layer 1): What I directly control=E2=80=94static pro=
mpts, curated knowledge bases, structured APIs. This provides predictable, =
auditable context delivery.
Probabilistic Context (Layer 2): The emergent layer=E2=80=94agent-initiated=
 searches, dynamic tool selection, recursive information gathering. This en=
ables adaptive intelligence but requires sophisticated orchestration.
As agentified workflows scale, this distinction becomes critical. I can't c=
ontrol what an agent discovers in extensive web searches, but I can design =
Layer 1 to guide Layer 2 toward useful discoveries while preventing context=
 explosion or drift.
The paradigm shift expands our thinking: from "How do I write the perfect m=
essage?" to "How do I design systems that naturally surface relevant contex=
t?"
The infrastructure for this broader approach exists today. Organizations ma=
stering context architecture alongside excellent prompting will define how =
intelligent systems behave tomorrow.
The article that follows explores exactly how to build these expanded syste=
ms.
